title: MakerBot Digitizer LaserCat - Layer thickness tests

description.text:
The MakerBot Digitizer 3D-scanned Laser Cat model was used in this test of different layer thicknesses. The cat was scaled down to 50 mm in height and then 3D printed at the following layer heights:
  • 0.40 mm (400 microns)
  • 0.30 mm (300 microns)
  • 0.20 mm (200 microns)
  • 0.10 mm (100 microns) - Average width of a strand of human hair
  • 0.05 mm (50 microns)
  • 0.02 mm (20 microns)
    All six cats where 3D printed on a MakerBot Replicator 2 with TRUE BLUE PLA plastic at 230 degrees C.
    All layers where 3D printed with MakerWare's standard values as follows:
    (400 microns) - 15% infill - perimeters 2 - speed 90 mm/s
    (300 microns) - 15% infill - perimeters 2 - speed 90 mm/s
    (200 microns) - 15% infill - perimeters 2 - speed 90 mm/s
    (100 microns) - 15% infill - perimeters 2 - speed 90 mm/s
    (50 microns) - 15% infill - perimeters 2 - speed 60 mm/s
    (20 microns) - 15% infill - perimeters 2 - speed 40 mm/s

description.text:
These badges are hard to come by without paying $80+ for a used one. A friend commissioned me to make a replacement for his car. It's not 100% accurate, I designed it based off an image I pulled off the internet. I am working on getting an actual badge that I can scan to make a more accurate model.

I did not use a font for the text.

No

Higher the better.

Solid

Notes:

I suggest printing in a higher resolution with a solid infill and ideally ABS.

Lightly sand and remove any printing defects
Spray multiple coats of a black high build primer to fill any gaps and voids
Cure overnight
Lightly sand
Tape off the "16V" portion of the emblem and spray the "GLI" letters with silver or aluminum
Cure overnight
Tape off the "GLI" letters and spray the "16V" red
Cure overnight
Tape off and cut out the Red and SIlver areas and spray the rest black
Cure overnight
FInish with a Gloss to semi-gloss clear coat.

I recommend allowing the paint to cure overnight between each color and before applying tape over fresh paint. This will give the best results and minimize risk of mistakes.

If printing with ABS you could vapor treat it but primer should fill the voids and make things look smooth.

title: LED module mounting bracket for Makerbot Thing-O-Matic

description.text: Light up the inside of your Makerbot Thing-O-Matic!  This mounting bracket supports an LED module that was originally designed to be used as a replacement for halogen (12VDC) lamps.  The screw holes on the brackets match the hole spacing of the "unused / extra" rod support on the top front of the Thing-O-Matic.  Inset nuts allow easy installation.  You don't even need to make holes in your Thing-O-Matic!

The spacing of the wire leads fits nicely into a molex-style connector with pin spacing of 0.156"  I use connectors to make it trivial to replace an LED module if one fails.  The LEDs are designed to run off of 12VDC.  They are "polarity indifferent" - I have plugged them with + and - in both directions and they work the same and draw the same amount of current!  extremely simple and handy.

title: LH Mount for Turbo Fan Duct, Taz5

description.text:
Mount allows a Very nice fan duct to be mounted on a Taz5 (plus others).
Here is a link to the cooler duct:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1025471

The mount both adapts the duct with the fan on the left-hand side, and provides the necessary extension pad for the Y axis limit swtich. This keeps the stage from smashing the fan into the side of the structure when you home the Y-axis.

You have to drill a couple of holes in the underside of the stock extruder support body. You remove the extruder, put it upside down and hold it in position with some sort of softjawed vice, and position the mount with the duct attached on the extruder. You want to center the extruder hotend on the fan duct. you then drill with a #39 (2.5mm) drill through the hole in the center of the mount and into the extruder support. Tap that hole (or simply use the 3mm screw to form the threads) and tighten the screw. Take out the rear screw holding the duct to the mount, and drill and tap that hole in the extruder support. Replace the screw in the duct. Wire the fan up and remount the extruder and you are done.

This fan duct obscures your view of the part while it is printing, but makes absolutely gorgeous parts.

You run the fan to ~50% maximum near the bed. When the head gets up away from the bed you can run it to ~60%. You might wish to replace the 24volt 30W heater in your extruder with a 24volt 40W heater. You can then run the fan all the way up.

title: Verlan Dress from New Skins with Francis Bitonti Studio

description.text: Remember when you first heard about 3D printing and someone said, "one day they'll even be able to 3D print clothing!" Well, here we go. Francis Bitonti, a multidisciplinary designer from New York City, organized a three-week workshop at Pratt that resulted in the creation of a 3D-printed dress. Bionti's designers built this dress with two MakerBot Replicator 2 Desktop 3D Printers and two different filaments: MakerBot PLA Filament, and MakerBot Flexible Filament, which is coming soon. MakerBot Flexible Filament is a polyester-based filament that is more flexible than PLA. It's ideal for constructing the parts of the dress that need to stretch and contract, adapting to the body's movement. The dress was made of 59 3D-printed pieces: 20 from PLA (for the harder, more skeleton-like sections), and 39 from MakerBot Flexible Filament (for the more dynamic, muscle-like parts). The pieces were glued together with Loctite Two Part Professional Heavy Duty 5 Minute Epoxy. The images show how they all fit together. All the parts of the dress took 400 hours to print and 24 hours to assemble. The MakerBot Flexible Filament was tied up the sides with leather straps, and the top was snapped into place with a plastic button. The current dimensions are for a 5'10" woman in a size 4, but you can tailor the dress to your own dimensions using the Blender file. We can't wait to spot you wearing yours. Interested in MakerBot Flexible Filament? Read more here.

title: No Calipers Required X and Y Axis Calibration Puzzle

description.text:
Designed to test X and Y calibration, this test will show you which axis needs work and by how much. NO CALIPERS REQUIRED!
"NOTICE: This test presumes that your calibration is close on x and y and that your extruder is dead on. Filament size can effect internal holes and exterior diameter if not correctly calibrated.
This is to reconcile the axis against each other and ensure printed parts will fit into each other as expected. 
The procedures mentioned here are my own and may have flaws I did not foresee."
The parts are labeled with the axis they are printed on length wise.
So, each axis and should show true. (Meaning the X Bar should fit the X slot even if the machine is off, same for Y bar and Y slot.)
The bars start with 20mm long and work down to 19.7mm. All bars are 5mm wide.
The slots are both 20mm long and 5.2mm wide (To allow you only test length).
I will post a full write up soon on the exact procedure to use this test.

The X bar should fit into the X slot. The ID of the slot is 20mm, the OD of the bar is also 20mm. 
(If they are too tight move down to the next size until you find the one that fits. Let's assume the X1 Bar fits the X slot.)
Use the X1 bar on the Y slot. If it fits the same as the X slot then you are calibrated. If not continue.
Too big (The smallest bar doesn't fit the opposite axis slot)- Your Y is not stepping as far as your X, increase the steps/mm.
Too small (One of the printed bars does fit, but is too loose length-wise.)- Move up one bar size if possible. If not, the steps are to long for that axis. You will have to reduce the steps.

The e-NABLE Prosthetic Emulator straps onto the arm of an able-bodied person to allow evaluation of upper limb prosthetic Terminal Devices (TDs). It can be an aid to clinicians when they train the amputee in the use of a prosthesis. It also is useful to designers as a testing device for experiencing experimental Terminal Device designs in use.

The Emulator is easy to fabricate with printed parts and a 1 1/4 inch plastic pipe. It attaches to the Terminal Device with the standard 1/2-20 screw thread (or M12 fine thread where metric is used). A standard Bowden cable can be fabricated from a String trimmer filament (or nylon 1.75mm printing filament) and a printed bead. The cable is attached to the Emulator (for elbow-powered operation) or to a shoulder harness in the conventional manner.

This is a new design that is evolving for use by e-NABLE volunteers to develop new experimental designs for assistive devices. The design and instructions will be updated from time to time based on testing and feedback.

description.text:
This is the mecanum wheel robot platform to go with my wheels (thing:1454685) which is currently a work in progress. The stepper motors (Nema17 65inoz) showed up this week but the stepper drivers A4988 will be some time. I'll post more as it is completed.

Currently the design rolls and accommodates either an arduino uno or mega with plenty of room for batteries or add-ons that would mate to the frame's bolt patterns, see layout pdf. My intention is to use (4) A4988 set onto (2) mini breadboards located in the center structure. Initially, I plan to use an external power supply before I move to fully wireless design/programming. (I have no program yet) From there I will think about end effectors or what this platform could be used for. I look forward to see what other people come up with!

The Statue of Liberty (Liberty Enlightening the World; French: La Liberté éclairant le monde) is a colossal neoclassical sculpture on Liberty Island in New York Harbor in New York City, in the United States. The copper statue, designed by Frédéric Auguste Bartholdi, a French sculptor, was built by Gustave Eiffel and dedicated on October 28, 1886. It was a gift to the United States from the people of France. The statue is of a robed female figure representing Libertas, the Roman goddess, who bears a torch and a tabula ansata (a tablet evoking the law) upon which is inscribed the date of the American Declaration of Independence, July 4, 1776. A broken chain lies at her feet. The statue is an icon of freedom and of the United States, and was a welcoming sight to immigrants arriving from abroad.

Bartholdi was inspired by French law professor and politician Édouard René de Laboulaye, who is said to have commented in 1865 that any monument raised to American independence would properly be a joint project of the French and American peoples. He may have been minded to honor the Union victory in the American Civil War and the end of slavery. Due to the post-war instability in France, work on the statue did not commence until the early 1870s. In 1875, Laboulaye proposed that the French finance the statue and the Americans provide the site and build the pedestal. Bartholdi completed the head and the torch-bearing arm before the statue was fully designed, and these pieces were exhibited for publicity at international expositions.

The torch-bearing arm was displayed at the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia in 1876, and in Madison Square Park in Manhattan from 1876 to 1882. Fundraising proved difficult, especially for the Americans, and by 1885 work on the pedestal was threatened due to lack of funds. Publisher Joseph Pulitzer of the New York World started a drive for donations to complete the project that attracted more than 120,000 contributors, most of whom gave less than a dollar. The statue was constructed in France, shipped overseas in crates, and assembled on the completed pedestal on what was then called Bedloe's Island. The statue's completion was marked by New York's first ticker-tape parade and a dedication ceremony presided over by President Grover Cleveland.

The statue was administered by the United States Lighthouse Board until 1901 and then by the Department of War; since 1933 it has been maintained by the National Park Service. The statue was closed for renovation for much of 1938. In the early 1980s, it was found to have deteriorated to such an extent that a major restoration was required. While the statue was closed from 1984 to 1986, the torch and a large part of the internal structure were replaced. After the September 11 attacks in 2001, it was closed for reasons of safety and security; the pedestal reopened in 2004 and the statue in 2009, with limits on the number of visitors allowed to ascend to the crown. The statue, including the pedestal and base, was closed for a year until October 28, 2012, so that a secondary staircase and other safety features could be installed; Liberty Island remained open. However, one day after the reopening, Liberty Island closed due to the effects of Hurricane Sandy in New York; the statue and island opened again on July 4, 2013. Public access to the balcony surrounding the torch has been barred for safety reasons since 1916

description.text:
Crickets are stupid. They need water to live, but if it's more than a drop or two they'll dive in and drown themselves. I have tried the gel stuff, a water dish with a sponge in it, etc. but have never found a good solution that doesn't dry out too quickly at the temperatures the crickets prefer, until I made this.

The holes in this waterer are small enough to keep water from running out, due to its surface tension, but if you line the tray portion with something fiberous, the fibers will draw out enough water for the crickets to drink from without drowning themselves. I just folded a paper towel to make several layers, and cut it to fit.

comments.text: These are designed to clamp X-Y rails (6mm for small printer) at four corners, and provide the upright threaded rod for the table lift with an equal/square mounting at the top. The two "extra" pulleys shown are to route the drive strings down to bottom mounted motors.the corner clamps are set in the  same direction at all corners to align the drive strings over the rails on the sides where the string reverses course from looping around the corner pulley. The rod jig from justinledwards combines 6 rods into 1 jig. This can allow the rods to be different lengths. I cut it down to 1 wide to be used one rod at a time to make them more exact. Bolt it onto 20x20 extrusion with the final length wanted .

The shape for the rod end was also for Traxxas ends which are a different shape than the one provided in the Folger Tech kit. I modified the shape to fit these.

Recommended to use thing 1218870 to cut the carbon fiber rod. Just use the posted STL. bolt in into a length of 20x20 extrusion with the wanted length measure between the thin slots. Push a razor blade into the slot and twist the tube with a drill. Works perfectly.

To use the jig, glue one end into the rod and let it set up. Then glue the other end and quickly push it into the jig to set up. You will end up with a set of exactly the same rods if done correctly. Enjoy!
